commit 29848ca81ca55860bd7f0d42312fab91552f04e6
Author: Hao Ge <hao.ge@linux.dev>

mm/alloc_tag: clear codetag for pages allocated before page_ext initialization

Due to initialization ordering, page_ext is allocated and initialized
relatively late during boot. Some pages have already been allocated
and freed before page_ext becomes available, leaving their codetag
uninitialized. Use a global array to track these pages and clear
their codetag refs later to avoid KASAN warnings.

> diff --git a/lib/alloc_tag.c b/lib/alloc_tag.c
> index 58991ab09d84..04846f80e7c3 100644
> --- a/lib/alloc_tag.c
> +++ b/lib/alloc_tag.c
[ ... ]
> @@ -758,8 +760,115 @@ static __init bool need_page_alloc_tagging(void)
>  	return mem_profiling_support;
>  }
>  
> +#ifdef CONFIG_MEM_ALLOC_PROFILING_DEBUG
> +/*
> + * Track page allocations before page_ext is initialized.
[ ... ]
> +static unsigned long early_pfns[EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX] __initdata;
> +static atomic_t early_pfn_count __initdata = ATOMIC_INIT(0);
> +
> +static void __init __alloc_tag_add_early_pfn(unsigned long pfn)
> +{
> +	int old_idx, new_idx;
> +
> +	do {
> +		old_idx = atomic_read(&early_pfn_count);

Since atomic_try_cmpxchg() automatically updates old_idx with the
current memory value on failure, is the atomic_read() inside the loop
redundant?

The standard pattern initializes old_idx once before the loop and lets
atomic_try_cmpxchg() handle the updates.

> +		if (old_idx >= EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX) {
> +			pr_warn_once("Early page allocations before page_ext init exceeded EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX (%d)\n",
> +				      EARLY_ALLOC_PFN_MAX);
> +			return;
> +		}
> +		new_idx = old_idx + 1;
> +	} while (!atomic_try_cmpxchg(&early_pfn_count, &old_idx, new_idx));
> +
> +	early_pfns[old_idx] = pfn;
> +}
> +
> +typedef void (*alloc_tag_add_func)(unsigned long pfn);
> +static alloc_tag_add_func __rcu alloc_tag_add_early_pfn_ptr __refdata =
> +		__alloc_tag_add_early_pfn;

If page_ext is disabled (e.g., via the page_ext=off kernel parameter)
or fails to initialize, page_ext_init() returns early and skips invoking
the .init callbacks.

This means clear_early_alloc_pfn_tag_refs() is never called, and
alloc_tag_add_early_pfn_ptr is never set to NULL.

Since memory allocation profiling can be enabled independently of
page_ext, subsequent page allocations will fall back to calling
alloc_tag_add_early_pfn().

After free_initmem() frees all __init and __initdata memory, will
this dereference the uncleared alloc_tag_add_early_pfn_ptr and jump to
a freed __init function? (The use of __refdata masks this lifecycle
mismatch from compiler warnings.)

> +
> +void alloc_tag_add_early_pfn(unsigned long pfn)
> +{
[ ... ]
> +static void __init clear_early_alloc_pfn_tag_refs(void)
> +{
[ ... ]
> +		if (pfn_valid(pfn)) {
> +			struct page *page = pfn_to_page(pfn);
> +			union pgtag_ref_handle handle;
> +			union codetag_ref ref;
> +
> +			if (get_page_tag_ref(page, &ref, &handle)) {
> +				/*
> +				 * An early-allocated page could be freed and reallocated
> +				 * after its page_ext is initialized but before we clear it.
> +				 * In that case, it already has a valid tag set.
> +				 * We should not overwrite that valid tag with CODETAG_EMPTY.
> +				 *
> +				 * Note: there is still a small race window between checking
> +				 * ref.ct and calling set_codetag_empty(). We accept this
> +				 * race as it's unlikely and the extra complexity of atomic
> +				 * cmpxchg is not worth it for this debug-only code path.
> +				 */
> +				if (ref.ct) {
> +					put_page_tag_ref(handle);
> +					continue;
> +				}
> +
> +				set_codetag_empty(&ref);
> +				update_page_tag_ref(handle, &ref);

Is it possible for a concurrent page allocation to occur between the
ref.ct check and the non-atomic update_page_tag_ref()?

If the page allocator assigns a valid codetag to the page during this
window, this update will overwrite it with CODETAG_EMPTY.

When the page is subsequently freed, alloc_tag_sub() will see
CODETAG_EMPTY and skip decrementing the allocation counters, which
would leak the profiling statistics.

Could this be fixed by using an atomic cmpxchg instead?

> +				put_page_tag_ref(handle);
> +			}
> +		}
> +
> +	}
> +}

